\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces  {\bf  a)} Schematic of the dynamics. Two ferromagnetically coupled ferromagnetic 1d Ising chains slide past one another at relative velocity $v$, and both couple to a bath at temperature $T$. {\bf  b)} Dynamic phase diagram in the $e^{\beta J}$-$v$ plane. In the blue shaded region, ${t_{\sf  mem}}\sim e^{\beta J ve^{\beta J}}$, while in the white region the scaling crosses over to the trivial ${t_{\sf  mem}}\sim e^{\beta J}$  { \color  {blue} \relax \fontsize  {8}{9.5pt}\selectfont  \abovedisplayskip 6\p@ plus2\p@ minus4\p@ \belowdisplayskip \abovedisplayskip \abovedisplayshortskip \z@ plus\p@ \belowdisplayshortskip 3\p@ plus\p@ minus2\p@ \def \leftmargin \leftmargini \topsep 4\p@ plus2\p@ minus2\p@ \parsep 2\p@ plus\p@ minus\p@ \itemsep \parsep {\leftmargin \leftmargini \topsep 3\p@ plus\p@ minus\p@ \parsep 2\p@ plus\p@ minus\p@ \itemsep \parsep }\textsf  {ethan: \textsl  {need constants in the exponents etc.}} }. The pink points are drawn by fixing $e^{\beta J}$, and then finding the smallest value of $v$ such that ${t_{\sf  mem}}(v) > 10 {t_{\sf  mem}}(0)$. {\bf  c)} A spacetime history of the magnetization, with $\beta = \infty , v = 2$. The indicated purple and red arrows denote interfaces that move with expected speeds $v + \delta $ and $v-\delta $, respectively. {\bf  d)} A history with $\beta = 2, v = 2$, with the minority domain in the initial state having size $l > {\xi _{\sf  er}}$. }}{2}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:overview}{{1}{2}{{\bf a)} Schematic of the dynamics. Two ferromagnetically coupled ferromagnetic 1d Ising chains slide past one another at relative velocity $v$, and both couple to a bath at temperature $T$. {\bf b)} Dynamic phase diagram in the $e^{\b J}$-$v$ plane. In the blue shaded region, $\tmem \sim e^{\b J ve^{\b J}}$, while in the white region the scaling crosses over to the trivial $\tmem \sim e^{\b J}$ \ethan {need constants in the exponents etc.}. The pink points are drawn by fixing $e^{\b J}$, and then finding the smallest value of $v$ such that $\tmem (v) > 10 \tmem (0)$. {\bf c)} A spacetime history of the magnetization, with $\b = \infty , v = 2$. The indicated purple and red arrows denote interfaces that move with expected speeds $v + \d $ and $v-\d $, respectively. {\bf d)} A history with $\b = 2, v = 2$, with the minority domain in the initial state having size $l > \ler $}{figure.1}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces  How a minority domain of size $l$ is eroded under ideal sliding dynamics at $\beta \rightarrow \infty $. The white regions have zero magnetization, and are metastable. The red arrows indicate interfaces that move with expected speed $v-\delta $, and the purple arrows those with speed $v+\delta $. The danger region ${\mathsf  {D}\mathsf  {R}}(l)$ indicated by the shaded triangle is the spacetime region where spin flips in the metastable zero-magnetization area can propagate to prevent the erosion of the $m=-2$ (red) part of the initial minority domain. }}{2}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:proof}{{2}{2}{How a minority domain of size $l$ is eroded under ideal sliding dynamics at $\b \ra \infty $. The white regions have zero magnetization, and are metastable. The red arrows indicate interfaces that move with expected speed $v-\d $, and the purple arrows those with speed $v+\d $. The danger region $\dr (l)$ indicated by the shaded triangle is the spacetime region where spin flips in the metastable zero-magnetization area can propagate to prevent the erosion of the $m=-2$ (red) part of the initial minority domain}{figure.2}{}}
